==Mining== {{main|Mining industry of South Africa}}
South African companies hold a considerable number of high value patents related to mining.<ref name=MMCP>{{cite book|last=Kaplan|first=David|title=South African mining equipment and related services: Growth, constraints and policy|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|isbn=978-1-77011-236-0|pages=8â9|url=http://www.cssr.uct.ac.za/sites/cssr.uct.ac.za/files/pubs/MMCP%20Paper%205_0.pdf|accessdate=27 June 2011|chapter=2. The Evidence for and the measurement of South Africaâs advanced technological competencies|year=2011|month=March}}</ref>
{{Expand section|date=June 2011}}
==Nuclear weapons programme== {{Main|South Africa and weapons of mass destruction}} [[File:South African nuclear bomb casings.jpg|thumb|Spare bomb casings from South Africa's nuclear weapon programme.]] During the 1960s and 1980s South Africa had been pursuing research into the development of [[nuclear weapons]] as well as [[biological weapon|biological]] and [[chemical weapons]]. South Africa was able to acquire [[Uranium]] from native ore deposits, and used [[Uranium enrichment|aerodynamic nozzle]] enrichment techniques to produce weapons-grade Uranium. Six bombs were constructed, with one still under construction before the termination of its nuclear weapons programme. It is alleged that South Africa had been collaborating with [[Israel]] to develop nuclear weapons and that it [[Vela Incident|possibly detonated one of its weapons]] over the [[Indian Ocean]] in a nuclear weapons test. South Africa dismantled its nuclear weapons programme in 1989, the first nation in the world to do so, and became a signatory of the [[Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty]] in 1991.
South Africa continues to use its surplus of Uranium as part of its nuclear energy programme, supplying the [[Koeberg Nuclear Power Station]] and [[SAFARI-1]] [[research reactor]]s. ==Government policy== Despite government efforts to encourage [[entrepreneurship]] in [[biotechnology]], [[information technology]] and other high technology fields, no other notable groundbreaking companies have been founded in South Africa.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} It is the expressed objective of the government to transition the economy to be more reliant on high technology, based on the realisation that South Africa cannot compete with Far Eastern economies in manufacturing, nor can the republic rely on its mineral wealth in perpetuity.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}
==Important advances made in South Africa== {{Expand section|date=June 2011}} * 1.5 [[Year#Symbols_y_and_yr|Mya]] - Earliest evidence of [[Control of fire by early humans|controlled use of fire by humans]] at [[Swartkrans]]<ref>{{cite journal|coauthors=C. K. Brain; A. Sillent|title=Evidence from the Swartkrans cave for the earliest use of fire|journal=nature|date=1988-12-01|volume=336|pages=464â466|doi=10.1038/336464a0|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v336/n6198/abs/336464a0.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|issue=6198}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rincon|first=Paul|title=Bones hint at first use of fire|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3557077.stm|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=BBC|date=22 March 2004}}</ref> * 1882, 1 September - [[Kimberley, Northern Cape|Kimberley]] becomes was the first city in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] and in [[Africa]] to have electric street lights.<ref name="kimberley-lights"/> * 1920 - [[Hendrik van der Bijl]] publishes ''The thermionic vacuum tube and its applications''.<ref>{{Internet Archive|id=thermionicvacuum00vandrich|name=The thermionic vacuum tube and its applications}}</ref> The standard textbook on the subject of [[vacuum tube]]s for more than 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr H J van der Bijl|url=http://www.saiee.org.za/content.php?pageID=264#|publisher=[[South African Institute of Electrical Engineers]]|accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref> * 1937 - The 17-D Yellow Fever vaccine is announced by [[Max Theiler]] * 1945 - [[Council for Scientific and Industrial Research]] was founded * 1955 - [[SASOL]] produces its first automotive fuel from coal<ref name="SASOL"/><ref name="iupac.org"/> * 1959 - [[Trevor Wadley]] invented the [[Tellurometer]], the first successful microwave distance measurement device. * 1962 - [[SANAE I]], the first South African [[Antarctic]] base is built.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanae - History|url=http://www.sanap.org.za/sanap_sanae/sanae_history.html|publisher=[[South African National Antarctic Programme]]|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SANAE|url=http://www.polarconservation.org/education/antarctic-bases/south-africa-and-antarctica/stations-bases-camps-and-refuges/sanae|publisher=Polarconservation|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref> * 1963 - The [[Dolos]] was developed in [[East London, South Africa|East London]] * 1965, 18 March - [[SAFARI-1]], the first nuclear reactor on the African continent, goes [[Critical mass|critical]] * 1967, 3 December - The first successful human-to-human heart transplant was performed by [[Christiaan Barnard]] at [[Groote Schuur Hospital]] * 1974 - The first [[automated pool cleaner]], the Kreepy Krauly, was introduced by Ferdinand Chauvier * 1975 - Development is started on a [[Helmet mounted display|helmet mounted sight]] system and the South African Air Force later become the first country to deploy these during combat.<ref>{{cite book|title=Vlamgat: The Story of the Mirage F1 in the South African Air Force|year=2000|publisher=30 Degrees South Publishers|pages=74|coauthors=Dick Lord, Willem Hechter|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref> * 1978 - [[South African Class 6E1, Series 4|SAR Class 6E1 (No. E1525)]] sets the [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] [[land speed record for rail vehicles]] at {{convert|245|kph}}.<ref>http://www.speedrecordclub.com/outrail.php</ref><ref>http://home.intekom.com/bluegrass/sites/steamsa/historical11.html</ref><ref>http://www.traintesting.com/SAR.htm</ref> * 1995 - [[Mark Shuttleworth]] founded [[Thawte]], an early Internet security company which is now the second largest [[certificate authority]] on the [[internet]]. * 1995 - The [[Natal Sharks Board]] starts marketing of the [[Protective Oceanic Device|Shark POD]], a personal device to deter sharks.<ref>{{cite web|title=SharkShield Testing|url=http://www.marinedirect.com.au/catalogue/c2432/p152845|publisher=Australia's Marine Direct|accessdate=27 June 2011}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Electrical Shark Repellent|url=http://www.shark.co.za/repel.htm|publisher=[[KwaZulu-Natal Sharks Board]]|accessdate=27 June 2011}}</ref> * 1999, 23 February - [[SUNSAT]], the first South African produced satellite was put in orbit by an American [[Delta II]] launch vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Background on the SUNSAT Experiment|url=http://genesis.jpl.nasa.gov/zope/GENESIS/Missions/SUNSAT|publisher=[[NASA]]|accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref>
==Nobel Laureates== * 1951, [[Max Theiler]], [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for his work on producing a [[Yellow fever]] vacine * 1979, [[Allan McLeod Cormack]], [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for pioneering work in [[X-ray computed tomography]] * 2002, [[Sydney Brenner]], [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for pioneering work in [[molecular biology]]
